<p>
In the sentence pattern @N1{{location}}@HI{{ni}}@N2{{}}@HI{{ga}}@HI{{@EM{{aru}}}}, a location is
presented as the topic and @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} focuses on what exists. @HI{{ni}} may be dropped.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{watashino@FG{{@KJ{{section^roof}}:heya}}ni@FG{{@KJ{{desk}}:tsukue}}gaarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There is a desk in my room.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In the sentence pattern @N1{{}}@HI{{ha}}@N2{{location}}@HI{{ni}}@HI{{@EM{{aru}}}}, a thing is presented as the topic and @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}}
focuses on where that thing is.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{east^capital}}:toukyou}}@KT{{dexizuni-rando}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{thousand^leaf^prefecture}}:chibaken'}}niarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Tokyo Disneyland is in Chiba Prefecture.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Note that @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} uses @HI{{ga}} to mark its object and not @HI{{wo}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{watashiha@KJ{{car}}gaarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I have a car.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} is only used to express the existence or possession of inanimate things.
For animate things, <a href="grammar-iru.html">@HI{{iru}}</a> is used.
</p>

<p>
The negative form of @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} is @HI{{nai}}.
</p>

<p>
When @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} is used to indicate having an animate object,
that object must have a close connection with the possessor.
</p>

<p>
When @HI{{@EM{{aru}}}} is used to for an event such as a party, @HI{{de}}
rather than @HI{{ni}} must be used.
</p>

